On World Refugee Day, the President acknowledges the 15 million refugees worldwide and expresses support for their search for a safe home. The President honors the courage of those forcibly displaced from countries like Libya, Syria, and Cote d'Ivoire. This year marks the 60th anniversary of the 1951 Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees, which outlines the rights and obligations of refugees and states. The President emphasizes that many people owe their lives to the help and protection they received from the international community. Additionally, this year is the 50th anniversary of the 1961 Convention on the Reduction of Statelessness, and the United States will continue to work towards empowering women and girls and providing opportunities for displaced and stateless women. The President stresses that protecting the most vulnerable is a crucial part of foreign policy and is both a moral imperative and in the interest of sustaining U.S. leadership. These efforts contribute to reconciliation, security, and well-being, aligning with critical U.S. national security interests.